@startuml 03_group_leader_workflow_prod
title BookRover — Group Leader Workflow (PROD)

skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
skinparam responseMessageBelowArrow true
skinparam roundcorner 8
skinparam defaultFontSize 13

actor       "Group Leader\n(Browser)"              as GL
participant "React App\n(CloudFront CDN)"          as FE
participant "API Gateway\n(HTTP API)"              as APIGW
participant "Lambda\n(FastAPI via Mangum)"         as BE
database    "DynamoDB\n(AWS Managed)"              as DB

note over FE, BE
  **PROD environment variables required**

  Frontend (set at build time via Vite):
    VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://<api-id>.execute-api.<region>.amazonaws.com

  Backend (Lambda environment variables):
    APP_ENV=prod
    BOOKROVER_TABLE_PREFIX=bookrover
    AWS_REGION=<region>
    COGNITO_USER_POOL_ID=<user-pool-id>
    COGNITO_REGION=<region>

  AWS Infrastructure:
    Lambda IAM Role — DynamoDB: Query/Scan on bookrover-group-leaders-prod,
                      bookrover-bookstores-prod, bookrover-sellers-prod,
                      bookrover-sales-prod (read-only for dashboard)
    API Gateway — throttling configured to prevent abuse
    CloudWatch — all Lambda invocations and errors captured
end note

note over GL, FE
  Precondition: group leader is logged in via Cognito.
  localStorage holds a valid Cognito IdToken.
  AuthContext holds: group_leader_id, roles=["group_leader"]
  All requests carry: Authorization: Bearer <CognitoIdToken>
  API Gateway validates token; Lambda verifies JWT signature on each call.
end note

== Dashboard loads at /dashboard ==

FE    -> APIGW : GET /group-leaders/{group_leader_id}/dashboard\n?bookstore_id={bookstore_id}\nAuthorization: Bearer <token>
APIGW -> BE   : Forward (after throttle/CORS check)

BE    -> BE   : Verify JWT → extract email → confirm group_leader role
BE    -> DB   : GetItem → bookrover-group-leaders-prod (GL record)
DB   --> BE   : { group_leader_id, name, bookstore_ids[], ... }
BE    -> DB   : GetItem → bookrover-bookstores-prod (selected bookstore)
DB   --> BE   : { bookstore_id, store_name, ... }
BE    -> DB   : Query bookrover-sellers-prod by group_leader_id + bookstore_id
DB   --> BE   : [Seller records]

loop for each seller
    BE -> DB : Query bookrover-sales-prod by seller_id + bookstore_id
    DB --> BE : [Sale records]
    BE -> BE : Aggregate: total_books_sold, total_amount_collected per seller
end

BE   --> APIGW : 200 DashboardResponse\n{\n  group_leader: { name },\n  bookstore: { store_name },\n  sellers: [\n    { seller_name, total_books_sold,\n      total_amount_collected }\n  ],\n  totals: { grand_total_books,\n            grand_total_amount }\n}
APIGW -> FE   : Forward response

== View dashboard data ==

FE    -> FE : Render sellers table\n(Seller Name | Books Sold | Money Collected)\nRender summary cards

== Sort sellers table ==

GL    -> FE : Click "Books Sold" or "Money Collected" column header
FE    -> FE : Toggle sort_by / sort_order — client-side sort (no API call)
FE    -> FE : Re-render sorted table

note right of FE
  Sorting is done entirely in the browser —
  no extra Lambda invocation or DynamoDB
  read. Cost-efficient for small seller lists.
end note

== Switch bookstore context (if multiple bookstores) ==

GL    -> FE : Click a different bookstore tab
FE    -> APIGW : GET /group-leaders/{group_leader_id}/dashboard\n?bookstore_id={new_bookstore_id}
APIGW -> BE   : Forward
BE    -> BE   : Verify JWT (re-verified on every request — stateless Lambda)
BE    -> DB   : Repeat fetch sequence for new bookstore
DB   --> BE   : Fresh data for selected bookstore
BE   --> APIGW : 200 DashboardResponse (new bookstore context)
APIGW -> FE   : Forward response
FE    -> FE   : Re-render dashboard with new context

note over GL, DB
  **Read-only view** — the Group Leader cannot create, edit,
  or delete sellers, books, or sales.
  Lambda is stateless — JWT is re-verified on every request;
  no session state is stored in Lambda memory.
end note

@enduml
